Drain the @tofu{280%grams} and chop into 2cm cubes. Pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

Place a #large pot{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once oil is hot, fry the tofu until slightly crispy, ~{7-10%minutes}. Shift frequently
to ensure it doesn't burn. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Remove from the pot and set aside. Cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, trim the @pak choi{1%unit}, then thinly slice widthways.

Trim the @carrot{1%unit}, then coarsely grate (no need to peel).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1%unit}.

Peel and grate the @ginger{1%unit}. Use a teaspoon to easily scrape away the peel.

Quarter the @lime{1%unit}. Thinly slice the @scallion{2%unit}. Thinly slice the @chilli{1%unit} widthways—at an angle.

Return the (now empty) #pot{} to medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

Add the onion and ginger to the pot and fry until softened, stirring
occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Add @water{600%ml}, @hoisin sauce{1%sachet} and @vegetable stock{2%sachets} to the pot.

Cover the pot and allow to simmer for ~{10-12%minutes}.

When 3-4 mins of cooking time remain add the pak choi, carrot, fried tofu and half
the sliced chilli (use less if you don't like spice) to the simmering stock. Cook
until the veg is softened.

Gently separate the @udon noodles{300%grams} and add them to the pot to warm through.

Season to taste with salt, pepper and lime juice.

Meanwhile, boil a #medium pot{} of water (for the eggs) over medium-high heat.

Once boiling, carefully add @?egg{2} (double for 4p).

Simmer gently for ~eggs{4-6%minutes} for soft-boiled eggs.

Once cooked to your preference, remove from the pot and add to a #bowl{} of cold
water —this will prevent them from cooking any more!

Carefully peel the eggs and halve lengthways. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide your pho style veg and tofu soup between bowls.

Lay the soft-boiled egg on top.

Garnish with sliced scallion, any remaining chilli and any remaining lime wedges.

> The egg is optional but adds a beautiful richness to the dish.